03988nam a22005775i 9780822378921DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223789217 a10.1515/97808223789212doi  a(DE-B1597)552766  a(OCoLC)1125547868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF3721 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a323.11981 aErazo, Juliet S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGoverning Indigenous Territories :bEnacting Sovereignty in the Ecuadorian Amazon /cJuliet S. Erazo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b6 photos, 2 tables, 10 maps, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tSelected Acronyms -- tAcknowledgments -- tMap -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one. History, Empowerment, and Rule -- tChapter two. Collectivist Utopias and "The Graveyard of Development Projects" -- tChapter three. The Property Debate -- tChapter four. Conservation and Environmental Subjects -- tChapter five. Everyday Forms of Territory Formation -- tConclusion. Making Citizens, Making Leaders, Making Territories 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGoverning Indigenous Territories illuminates a paradox of modern indigenous lives. In recent decades, native peoples from Alaska to Cameroon have sought and gained legal title to significant areas of land, not as individuals or families but as large, collective organizations. Obtaining these collective titles represents an enormous accomplishment; it also creates dramatic changes. Once an indigenous territory is legally established, other governments and organizations expect it to act as a unified political entity, making decisions on behalf of its population and managing those living within its borders. A territorial government must mediate between outsiders and a not-always-united population within a context of constantly shifting global development priorities. The people of Rukullakta, a large indigenous territory in Ecuador, have struggled to enact sovereignty since the late 1960s. Drawing broadly applicable lessons from their experiences of self-rule, Juliet S. Erazo shows how collective titling produces new expectations, obligations, and subjectivities within indigenous territories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aIndians of South AmericazAmazon River RegionxPolitics and government. 0aIndians of South AmericazEcuadorxPolitics and government. 0aIndigenous peopleszAmazon River RegionxPolitics and government. 0aIndigenous peopleszEcuadorxPolitics and government. 0aSovereignty. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822378921zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822378921423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822378921.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles